ANTHRAX, HUMAN, LIVESTOCK - GHANA (08): (UPPER EAST) VACCINATION HALTED
***********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[Due to a technical problem with our email system, some subscribers did not receive this post. We apologize if you are receiving a duplicate. - Mod.LM]

Date: 28 May 2012
Source: Daily Guide [edited]
http://www.dailyguideghana.com/?p=49455


Anthrax Kills More
------------------
An additional 2 persons have been killed by the deadly anthrax disease after consuming the carcass of an anthrax infected cow. The 2 were among 3 people who ate the carcass of an anthrax infected cow at the Nabiisi section of Balungu in the Bongo District of the Upper East region. 2 persons earlier died at the Googo community in the Bawku West District of the Upper East region after consuming the meat of animals suspected to have suffered anthrax infection. Some cattle owners do not bury the carcass after sudden death, but slaughter and sprinkle concoction on them for sale. [This is essentially just a re-run of what was posted on 25 May 2012 in 20120518.1137531. Now read on. - Mod.MHJ]

Daily Guide gathered that the Bongo District Assembly and the District of office of the Ministry of Food and Agriculture office have halted the vaccination programme in the Bongo district due to the lack of resources to convey veterinary officers to various parts of the district.

From 11 to 22 May 2012, some veterinary officers used their [own] resources to travel from Bongo to Balungu and its environs to continue the vaccination. [But] they have resolved to stop the programme until the District Assembly provides them with money [for] travel to the communities to continue the vaccination programme.

Recently, a combined team of Health and Veterinary Officers, Zoomlion and an elder from the Bonaba's palace, went to Balungu and retrieved the remaining portion of a "prepared" meat and other dead cattle from the owners for proper burial to avert the spread of the disease.

According the Upper East Regional Officer of the Veterinary Service, Dr.Thomas Anyorikeya, a total of 2700 livestock were vaccinated in the Balungu area and other parts of the Bongo District from 11 to 22 May 2012. He said people have been advised to seek medical treatment.

This is not the 1st time an anthrax outbreak has been recorded in the Bongo district, but some people have tried to eat the carcasses of dead animals even though they have been sternly cautioned against such practice.

The Regional Veterinary Officer told Daily Guide that the sprouting stage of the grass is very dangerous because the anthrax spores are just beneath the grass [in the root mass and get consumed when a grazing cow tugs it all out when grazing. - Mod.MHJ]. Currently, farmers are expected to pay 20Gp [USD 10.65] to vaccinate a cow, bull, sheep, goat, pig, dog or donkey but some of them are refusing to pay for the vaccination of their animals.

[Byline: Ebo Bruce-Quansah, Bongo]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap alerts
